509
00:32:59,018 --> 00:33:01,938
Everybody, hands up! Reach high! And...

510
00:33:02,021 --> 00:33:03,356
[flapping lips]

511
00:33:03,439 --> 00:33:04,649
[all flapping lips]

512
00:33:04,732 --> 00:33:05,983
[Mr Davenport] Guys, can you please...

513
00:33:06,818 --> 00:33:08,778
[indistinct chattering]

514
00:33:08,861 --> 00:33:14,117
Okay. You... You guys, skooch.
Sit. Just be closer.

515
00:33:14,200 --> 00:33:15,493
Ladies and gentlemen.

516
00:33:15,576 --> 00:33:17,620
Stay. Stay, good.

517
00:33:17,704 --> 00:33:21,666
Hey, hey. What's your name?

518
00:33:21,791 --> 00:33:22,792
Auggie.

519
00:33:23,543 --> 00:33:24,836
Nice boots.

520
00:33:26,754 --> 00:33:28,631
Great. Thanks.

521
00:33:30,299 --> 00:33:35,847
Okay, everybody, here we go.
We're skooching and say, "Cheese."

522
00:33:35,930 --> 00:33:38,057
[all] Cheese!

523
00:33:40,351 --> 00:33:43,688
[Auggie] School became...
Well, I got used to it.

524
00:33:43,771 --> 00:33:45,565
Except for dodgeball.

525
00:33:45,648 --> 00:33:47,859
What evil man invented dodgeball?

526
00:33:49,694 --> 00:33:54,323
But my least favourite zone at school 
is courtyard.

527
00:33:54,407 --> 00:33:56,367
Because the whole school's there.

528
00:33:57,660 --> 00:34:01,497
No one does anything mean.
Or says anything. Or laughs.

529
00:34:01,581 --> 00:34:05,668
They all just look, then look away, 
then look back.

530
00:34:05,752 --> 00:34:07,503
They're just being normal kids.

531
00:34:07,587 --> 00:34:12,050
I kinda wanna tell them, 
"Hey, I know I look weird, but it's okay."

532
00:34:12,133 --> 00:34:15,762
I mean, if Chewbacca started
going to school here one day,

533
00:34:15,845 --> 00:34:17,889
I'd probably stare at him a bit, too.

534
00:34:17,972 --> 00:34:19,515
[Chewbacca gurgles throatily]

535
00:34:29,150 --> 00:34:31,486
I'm sorry if my staring
made you feel weird.

536
00:34:31,611 --> 00:34:33,112
[grunting]

537
00:34:38,701 --> 00:34:41,996
In order for any of us to see,
we need light.

538
00:34:42,079 --> 00:34:47,752
So, right now light is bouncing off
this card travelling through the air,

539
00:34:47,835 --> 00:34:49,712
through the glass, to your eye.

540
00:34:49,837 --> 00:34:52,340
But what if we added water?

541
00:34:58,638 --> 00:35:01,057
-[all] Whoa!
-[chuckles]

542
00:35:01,140 --> 00:35:02,600
Whoa, indeed.

543
00:35:03,226 --> 00:35:08,523
Any time light passes from one material
or medium to another, it bends.

544
00:35:09,440 --> 00:35:11,734
This bending of light is also known as...

545
00:35:15,112 --> 00:35:16,572
Refraction.

546
00:35:16,656 --> 00:35:17,698
Very good, Auggie.

547
00:35:19,158 --> 00:35:20,576
Jack, you okay?

548
00:35:20,660 --> 00:35:22,787
-Yeah, yeah, refraction.
-Good.

549
00:35:22,870 --> 00:35:25,832
Clear your desks. Pop quiz.

550
00:35:25,957 --> 00:35:27,625
[all groaning]

551
00:36:03,703 --> 00:36:04,871
[whispers] Hurry.

552
00:36:34,609 --> 00:36:36,152
[kids chattering]

553
00:36:38,321 --> 00:36:39,864
Hey, Jack, come sit here.

554
00:36:44,535 --> 00:36:45,870
In a sec.

555
00:36:48,539 --> 00:36:49,498
Where's he going?

556
00:36:51,250 --> 00:36:52,251
Hey.

557
00:36:52,335 --> 00:36:53,836
Thanks for your help today.

558
00:36:54,503 --> 00:36:55,546
No problem.

559
00:36:56,297 --> 00:37:00,009
And don't worry, I got a couple
wrong so Ms Petosa wouldn't know.

560
00:37:00,134 --> 00:37:02,970
I'm not worried.
The worst they can do is kick me out.

561
00:37:04,847 --> 00:37:06,891
Not loving school either, huh?

562
00:37:06,974 --> 00:37:08,226
Oh, it's great.

563
00:37:08,309 --> 00:37:11,145
[chuckles] I wanted to go to Wayne Middle.

564
00:37:11,228 --> 00:37:12,980
The one with the great sports teams.

565
00:37:13,105 --> 00:37:14,607
Then why'd you come here?

566
00:37:15,650 --> 00:37:17,193
They gave me the scholarship.

567
00:37:21,322 --> 00:37:26,244
Well, if you need help in science,
you can come to my house after school.

568
00:37:26,327 --> 00:37:28,829
You know, if you want.

569
00:37:28,955 --> 00:37:30,539
Great. Thanks!

570
00:37:33,751 --> 00:37:35,002
What's wrong?

571
00:37:35,795 --> 00:37:38,005
I just don't like eating
in front of people.

572
00:37:38,089 --> 00:37:39,590
What do you mean?

573
00:37:39,674 --> 00:37:41,759
It's a long story, but when I eat,

574
00:37:41,842 --> 00:37:45,012
I think I chew
like some prehistoric swamp turtle.

575
00:37:45,096 --> 00:37:47,139
No joke? Me too!

576
00:37:48,266 --> 00:37:49,976
[both laughing]

577
00:37:50,059 --> 00:37:51,811
[Auggie] Now there's tuna on your face.

578
00:37:51,894 --> 00:37:53,938
Yeah! Tuna, man!

579
00:37:54,021 --> 00:37:56,232
No, no, no, let me show you how it's done.

580
00:37:56,315 --> 00:37:59,568
-[chuckles]
-[mimics chomping]

581
00:37:59,652 --> 00:38:01,112
[both chucking]

582
00:38:01,821 --> 00:38:03,155
Dude, that's even more gross.

583
00:38:18,379 --> 00:38:20,256
I'm going as Boba Fett this year.

584
00:38:20,339 --> 00:38:23,801
I like Halloween,
but Christmas is still the best holiday.

585
00:38:23,884 --> 00:38:26,387
[Auggie] No way. Halloween is the best.

586
00:38:26,470 --> 00:38:29,056
A pillowcase of candy
versus two weeks off school.

587
00:38:29,140 --> 00:38:30,057
You're nuts.

588
00:38:30,975 --> 00:38:32,852
-[barks]
-You see?

589
00:38:32,935 --> 00:38:33,811
Even your dog agrees.

590
00:38:35,730 --> 00:38:37,565
Hey, Mom, is it okay if Jack comes over?

591
00:38:40,109 --> 00:38:41,152
Yes!

592
00:38:41,277 --> 00:38:42,903
Thanks, Mrs P.

593
00:38:42,987 --> 00:38:45,197
I mean, you get snow on Christmas.

594
00:38:45,281 --> 00:38:47,116
But you can get snow on Halloween.

595
00:38:47,700 --> 00:38:49,702
-[Jack] How?
-If you live in Alaska

596
00:38:49,785 --> 00:38:51,078
or there's a blizzard.

597
00:38:51,162 --> 00:38:53,122
[exhales] I've got to be cool.

598
00:38:56,167 --> 00:38:58,461
[both grunting]

599
00:39:09,263 --> 00:39:11,599
You ever thought about
having plastic surgery?

600
00:39:12,141 --> 00:39:14,310
No, I've never thought about it. Why?

601
00:39:15,061 --> 00:39:16,395
[chuckles]

602
00:39:16,479 --> 00:39:19,231
Dude, this is after plastic surgery!

603
00:39:19,356 --> 00:39:21,817
It takes a lot of work to look this good.

604
00:39:21,901 --> 00:39:24,737
-[both laughing]
-Oh, my God! Oh, my God.

605
00:39:24,820 --> 00:39:25,821
[Auggie and Jake] One, two, 

606
00:39:25,946 --> 00:39:28,199
three, four, I declare a thumb war.

607
00:39:28,282 --> 00:39:30,910
Bow, kiss, begin.

608
00:39:50,429 --> 00:39:51,430
Nate.

609
00:39:53,849 --> 00:39:54,892
Fire.

610
00:40:00,815 --> 00:40:02,608
[inaudible]

611
00:40:04,610 --> 00:40:07,780
Okay, everybody, if you can't see
the camera, the camera can't see you.

612
00:40:07,863 --> 00:40:10,032
Now, let's improv like we know
what we're doing.

613
00:40:10,116 --> 00:40:12,493
Okay, everybody say, "Stella!"

614
00:40:12,576 --> 00:40:13,786
-[all] Stella!
-[camera clicks]

615
00:40:23,796 --> 00:40:25,464
So I can't figure you out.

616
00:40:25,548 --> 00:40:26,757
What?

617
00:40:27,466 --> 00:40:30,052
Um, I can't figure you out.

618
00:40:30,136 --> 00:40:31,220
Oh?

619
00:40:31,303 --> 00:40:34,849
Well, most theatre people won't
stop talking about themselves.

620
00:40:34,932 --> 00:40:36,392
But you don't talk.

621
00:40:37,434 --> 00:40:38,894
I... I listen.

622
00:40:39,854 --> 00:40:40,896
Me too.

623
00:40:41,313 --> 00:40:42,189
I know.

624
00:40:42,815 --> 00:40:45,234
Oh. [chuckles] So you do pay attention.

625
00:40:46,652 --> 00:40:48,279
Okay, that's a start. Uh...

626
00:40:48,821 --> 00:40:51,365
I'm a good listener, so tell me something.

627
00:40:51,449 --> 00:40:53,075
Who are you gonna audition for?

628
00:40:53,200 --> 00:40:56,996
Um, I'm not really the Our Town type.

629
00:40:57,079 --> 00:41:00,416
Oh, come on.
Don't be the "run lights girl."

630
00:41:00,499 --> 00:41:01,458
Should be Emily.

631
00:41:02,501 --> 00:41:03,502
The lead?

632
00:41:03,878 --> 00:41:06,088
Look, your family can't cheer
for you in a booth.

633
00:41:06,881 --> 00:41:08,257
Oh, they're... They're pretty busy.

634
00:41:08,340 --> 00:41:10,384
I don't think they would
cheer for me anyway.

635
00:41:10,467 --> 00:41:12,303
Come on, there's not one person

636
00:41:12,386 --> 00:41:14,346
in your family who would applaud you?

637
00:41:15,973 --> 00:41:17,266
My grandmother.

638
00:41:18,142 --> 00:41:19,810
There you go. Bring her.

639
00:41:21,145 --> 00:41:22,229
I can't.

640
00:41:25,316 --> 00:41:27,818
Well, then I'll applaud you.

641
00:41:29,361 --> 00:41:31,739
Why are you being so nice to me?

642
00:41:32,573 --> 00:41:35,910
Because you're an only child.
We have to stick together.

643
00:41:38,746 --> 00:41:40,289
Think about it. Okay?

644
00:41:43,626 --> 00:41:46,462
And, uh,
your grandmother's still cheering you on.

645
00:41:55,512 --> 00:41:57,139
[grandmother] I know you.

646
00:41:58,432 --> 00:42:03,062
And I love you more
than anything in the world.

647
00:42:04,897 --> 00:42:07,358
What about Auggie?

648
00:42:07,441 --> 00:42:09,276
I love your brother.

649
00:42:10,319 --> 00:42:14,406
But he has a lot of angels
looking out for him.

650
00:42:16,033 --> 00:42:17,826
And you have me.

651
00:42:20,829 --> 00:42:22,081
Yeah.

652
00:42:24,541 --> 00:42:26,293
You are everywhere.

653
00:42:27,878 --> 00:42:28,921
And...

654
00:42:31,173 --> 00:42:32,967
...you are my favourite.

655
00:42:34,468 --> 00:42:36,428
You're my favourite, too, Grams.

656
00:43:02,997 --> 00:43:05,291
Mom, Daisy ruined my Boba Fett costume!

657
00:43:05,374 --> 00:43:08,502
What? Where have you been? It's very late.

658
00:43:08,585 --> 00:43:10,254
-I'm sorry.
-She threw up all over it.

659
00:43:10,337 --> 00:43:12,590
Okay, well, you'll just have
to wear your costume from last year.

660
00:43:12,673 --> 00:43:16,343
But I told Jack
I was going as Boba Fett, not Ghostface.

661
00:43:16,427 --> 00:43:19,305
Well, tomorrow is Halloween.
And all the shops are closed.

662
00:43:19,388 --> 00:43:21,682
And my artistic hands are busy
making meatloaf.

663
00:43:21,765 --> 00:43:22,641
So you do the math.

664
00:43:22,725 --> 00:43:24,101
Fine!

665
00:43:26,979 --> 00:43:28,022
Do you need some help, Mom?

666
00:43:28,105 --> 00:43:29,315
What?

667
00:43:29,398 --> 00:43:30,441
Some help.

668
00:43:30,524 --> 00:43:32,943
Oh, uh, yes, thank you.

669
00:43:33,652 --> 00:43:35,529
Er, mince that rosemary, please.

670
00:43:39,074 --> 00:43:40,826
Where did you say you were?

671
00:43:42,286 --> 00:43:46,332
I, uh... I went to Coney Island.

672
00:43:56,258 --> 00:43:59,219
How about you stay home
from school tomorrow? Hmm?

673
00:43:59,303 --> 00:44:02,139
It's Halloween.
We can make it a three-day weekend.

674
00:44:02,222 --> 00:44:03,599
Spend some time together.

675
00:44:04,683 --> 00:44:06,560
Yeah. Yeah, that would be really nice.

676
00:44:08,062 --> 00:44:09,063
Yeah?

677
00:44:10,230 --> 00:44:11,231
Okay, good.

678
00:44:13,192 --> 00:44:15,027
Peppers? I don't want peppers.

679
00:44:15,110 --> 00:44:17,279
-Peppers give Daddy gas.
-[chuckles]

680
00:44:20,240 --> 00:44:23,577
[Auggie] I don't care what Jack Will 
says about Christmas.

681
00:44:25,037 --> 00:44:26,080
[Nate] Hey, Auggie!

682
00:44:28,457 --> 00:44:33,045
[Auggie] For me, Halloween
is the best holiday in the world.

683
00:44:34,380 --> 00:44:37,257
It's so awesome
when I'm wearing the costume!

684
00:44:37,341 --> 00:44:40,886
I usually walk with my head down 
to avoid being seen.

685
00:44:40,969 --> 00:44:44,848
But on Halloween,
I walk with my head up high.

686
00:44:51,188 --> 00:44:53,190
I don't even know who that was.

687
00:44:53,273 --> 00:44:55,984
He didn't even know who I was. 
It's so cool.

688
00:44:56,068 --> 00:44:58,320
Especially because people
don't like to touch me

689
00:44:58,404 --> 00:45:00,739
because they think I'm contagious.

690
00:45:00,823 --> 00:45:05,160
Oh, yeah, Chewie! Up high!
Boom goes the dynamite!

691
00:45:07,704 --> 00:45:10,457
[kids laughing]

692
00:45:12,167 --> 00:45:14,503
It really does look like him.

693
00:45:14,586 --> 00:45:16,130
-This part right?
-[Amos] Yeah.

694
00:45:16,338 --> 00:45:19,675
[Julian] I mean, he's always reminded me
of, like, the shrunken head, you know?

695
00:45:19,758 --> 00:45:20,968
[Amos] Or an orc.
[Julian] Yeah.

696
00:45:21,093 --> 00:45:24,138
If I looked like him, I'd swear
I'd put a hood over my face every day.

697
00:45:24,263 --> 00:45:27,391
[Jack] If I looked like him,
I think I'd kill myself.

698
00:45:27,474 --> 00:45:28,976
Why do you hang out with him
so much, Jack?

699
00:45:29,101 --> 00:45:30,811
[Miles] Yeah.
[Jack] I don't know.

700
00:45:33,313 --> 00:45:34,815
Tushman asked me to be his welcome buddy

701
00:45:34,898 --> 00:45:37,609
and now
he just follows me around everywhere.

702
00:45:37,693 --> 00:45:40,154
[Julian] Well, that must stink!
That must stink.

703
00:45:40,237 --> 00:45:41,447
[kids laughing]

704
00:45:41,530 --> 00:45:43,198
[Amos] Oh, yeah. Just like him.

705
00:45:43,282 --> 00:45:45,033
[kids continue laughing]

706
00:45:47,578 --> 00:45:49,288
-[growls]
-[laughing]

707
00:45:57,421 --> 00:45:59,423
Nobody puts Baby in the corner.

708
00:46:03,510 --> 00:46:07,639
Always blows my mind how much Daddy
looks like Patrick Swayze in this movie.

709
00:46:07,764 --> 00:46:10,184
-Ew!
-[chuckling]

710
00:46:10,267 --> 00:46:11,894
Ew, no!

711
00:46:13,854 --> 00:46:15,772
Honey, tell me
what's going on with Miranda?

712
00:46:17,691 --> 00:46:20,652
It's not... It's not just the pink hair.

713
00:46:21,278 --> 00:46:22,404
She's just...

714
00:46:23,405 --> 00:46:24,615
She won't even talk to me.

715
00:46:26,575 --> 00:46:30,287
I had a friend in high school.
We went through this exact same thing.

716
00:46:30,496 --> 00:46:33,373
And what I did, which fixed it
almost immediately...

717
00:46:33,457 --> 00:46:35,000
Yeah?

718
00:46:35,083 --> 00:46:40,797
Was, um, to eat an entire
jack-o'-lantern bucket of candy.

719
00:46:41,590 --> 00:46:43,342
-[chuckles]
-[phone ringing]

720
00:46:46,303 --> 00:46:47,846
Mmm. Hello.

721
00:46:48,805 --> 00:46:50,349
Yes, Mr Tushman.

722
00:46:51,892 --> 00:46:53,519
He's nauseous?

723
00:46:53,602 --> 00:46:55,103
Does he have a fever?

724
00:46:55,896 --> 00:46:57,105
What did the nurse say?

725
00:46:57,189 --> 00:46:58,440
I'm so sorry.

726
00:46:58,524 --> 00:47:02,319
All right. Okay. Thank you.
I will be right there.

727
00:47:02,402 --> 00:47:05,239
Honey, I have to go,
your brother just threw up at school.

728
00:47:07,658 --> 00:47:09,701
[indistinct chatter on TV]

729
00:47:10,702 --> 00:47:11,870
[TV turns off]

730
00:47:14,831 --> 00:47:16,291
[clattering]

731
00:47:24,383 --> 00:47:25,801
[sobbing softly]

732
00:47:25,884 --> 00:47:28,178
[Isabel] Nate, do you know
where his helmet is?

733
00:47:28,262 --> 00:47:30,138
He's asking for it
and I've looked everywhere.

734
00:47:31,139 --> 00:47:32,432
I don't know. Something at school.

735
00:47:32,516 --> 00:47:34,309
He won't say.
He won't come out of his room.

736
00:47:34,393 --> 00:47:36,645
And now he says he doesn't even
wanna go trick-or-treating.

737
00:47:37,771 --> 00:47:40,691
I know. Okay. Thank you. Just get here.

738
00:47:56,331 --> 00:47:57,833
[Via] Come on, get ready.

739
00:47:57,916 --> 00:47:59,835
It's almost time for the Halloween parade.

740
00:47:59,918 --> 00:48:01,336
You're supposed to knock!

741
00:48:02,921 --> 00:48:05,382
-[knocks on table]
-Go away!

742
00:48:07,676 --> 00:48:11,221
Mom says you won't say what happened.

743
00:48:11,305 --> 00:48:13,390
Did someone say something?

744
00:48:13,473 --> 00:48:15,559
Someone always says something!

745
00:48:15,642 --> 00:48:16,810
Well, tell me what happened.

746
00:48:16,893 --> 00:48:18,478
It's none of your business!

747
00:48:18,562 --> 00:48:21,481
You took my day with Mom,
so it is my business.

748
00:48:23,900 --> 00:48:27,195
I heard Jack Will talking
about me behind my back.

749
00:48:27,279 --> 00:48:29,615
He said he'd kill himself
if he looked like me.

750
00:48:29,698 --> 00:48:33,493
Jack Will? Isn't he the nice one?

751
00:48:33,577 --> 00:48:35,704
[Auggie] There are no nice ones!

752
00:48:35,787 --> 00:48:38,373
I wish I'd never gone
to school in the first place!

753
00:48:38,457 --> 00:48:40,751
But you were liking school.
I know you were.

754
00:48:40,834 --> 00:48:42,336
I hate it, okay? I hate it!

755
00:48:47,174 --> 00:48:50,677
Auggie, I'm sorry, but you're not
the only one who has bad days.

756
00:48:51,428 --> 00:48:55,474
Bad days? Do people avoid touching you?

757
00:48:55,557 --> 00:48:58,852
When a person accidentally touches you,
do they call it "the plague"?

758
00:48:59,645 --> 00:49:00,771
No.

759
00:49:00,854 --> 00:49:02,481
Jack Will was all I had.

760
00:49:02,564 --> 00:49:05,734
So just don't compare
your bad days at school to mine, okay?

761
00:49:05,817 --> 00:49:07,027
Okay.

762
00:49:12,949 --> 00:49:14,117
Hey.

763
00:49:14,951 --> 00:49:17,245
Did you notice that Miranda
doesn't come around any more?

764
00:49:17,329 --> 00:49:18,455
What?

765
00:49:18,872 --> 00:49:20,957
You didn't. Shocker.

766
00:49:22,417 --> 00:49:26,797
Yeah, she went away to camp this summer
and now she doesn't like me any more.

767
00:49:26,880 --> 00:49:28,090
Why?

768
00:49:29,049 --> 00:49:31,468
Because school sucks.

769
00:49:32,386 --> 00:49:34,388
And people change.

770
00:49:34,471 --> 00:49:38,100
So if you wanna be a normal kid,
Auggie, then those are the rules.

771
00:49:39,601 --> 00:49:42,771
So, let's go trick-or-treating.

772
00:49:43,313 --> 00:49:45,273
Okay?

773
00:49:45,357 --> 00:49:49,361
Because right now
we're each other's best friends.

774
00:49:52,781 --> 00:49:53,824
Really?

775
00:49:54,408 --> 00:49:55,409
Yes.

776
00:49:56,326 --> 00:49:58,453
So, come on.

777
00:50:00,122 --> 00:50:01,957
I'll let you have all my Halloween candy.

778
00:50:05,919 --> 00:50:06,920
[indistinct chatter]

779
00:50:07,003 --> 00:50:08,380
[Auggie] I'll trade you my apples.

780
00:50:08,463 --> 00:50:09,756
[Via] Okay, no.

781
00:50:09,840 --> 00:50:11,758
I know that I said that
you could have all my candy,

782
00:50:11,842 --> 00:50:14,344
but I was really just saying that
to get you out of the house.

783
00:50:14,428 --> 00:50:15,429
[Auggie] What about the chocolate?

784
00:50:15,512 --> 00:50:16,805
-[Via] No.
-And the Smarties?

785
00:50:16,888 --> 00:50:19,307
Gummies, licorice, the Reese's,
the Hersheys.

786
00:50:19,391 --> 00:50:20,851
-No!
-And everything else.

787
00:50:20,934 --> 00:50:23,270
All right, I'll let you have all my candy.

788
00:50:28,692 --> 00:50:30,444
[Mr Davenport] Okay, Via.

789
00:50:30,527 --> 00:50:33,321
You are next, please.
Let's hear it for Via.

790
00:50:55,886 --> 00:50:57,095
[exhales]

791
00:50:59,055 --> 00:50:59,931
Daisy,

792
00:51:01,892 --> 00:51:04,770
do you wanna help me
take back my corner office?

793
00:51:14,905 --> 00:51:16,823
Hey, Auggie! You feeling better?

794
00:51:20,577 --> 00:51:23,246
Are you okay, Auggie?

795
00:51:24,456 --> 00:51:25,290
Yeah.

796
00:51:26,208 --> 00:51:28,502
Sure? 'Cause you're acting really weird.

797
00:51:28,627 --> 00:51:29,920
I'm okay, Jack, okay?

798
00:51:33,215 --> 00:51:34,508
Okay.

799
00:51:40,222 --> 00:51:41,056
[sighs]

800
00:51:46,228 --> 00:51:47,813
They want me to do what?

801
00:51:47,938 --> 00:51:49,856
[sighs] Give a tour through the school.

802
00:51:50,440 --> 00:51:54,027
-But, Mom, it's summer vacation.
-I know.

803
00:51:54,110 --> 00:51:56,863
But your teachers told Mr Tushman
you're known as a good egg.

804
00:51:56,988 --> 00:51:58,990
-No, I'm a bad egg.
-You're a good egg.

805
00:52:00,033 --> 00:52:03,078
And I'm actually really proud
they thought of you for this.

806
00:52:03,203 --> 00:52:05,080
Mom, enough with the guilt.

807
00:52:05,163 --> 00:52:07,165
And you know
they gave you a scholarship, right?

808
00:52:07,749 --> 00:52:09,000
Mom...

809
00:52:12,254 --> 00:52:14,047
Who else is doing it?

810
00:52:14,172 --> 00:52:16,550
Uh, Charlotte and Julian.

811
00:52:16,633 --> 00:52:18,176
-No.
-Why, what's wrong?

812
00:52:18,426 --> 00:52:21,596
Charlotte will just talk about Broadway
the whole time.

813
00:52:21,680 --> 00:52:24,516
And Julian is the biggest
phony on the planet.

814
00:52:24,599 --> 00:52:26,560
So I'm sorry, but no.

815
00:52:32,607 --> 00:52:34,317
Jack, it's for that boy.

816
00:52:34,401 --> 00:52:35,610
Who?

817
00:52:35,735 --> 00:52:37,946
The one from the ice cream shop.

818
00:52:39,990 --> 00:52:41,074
Oh.

819
00:52:41,658 --> 00:52:42,868
Yeah.

820
00:52:43,243 --> 00:52:46,997
So if a nice kid like your little brother
cries when he sees him,

821
00:52:47,080 --> 00:52:49,666
what kind of a chance
do you think he has in middle school?

822
00:52:55,213 --> 00:52:56,381
[sighs] Okay.

823
00:52:57,966 --> 00:52:58,925
Thank you, kiddo.

824
00:53:05,390 --> 00:53:08,685
[Jack] Four things I've learned
about Auggie Pullman.

825
00:53:08,768 --> 00:53:12,230
First of all, you do get used to his face.

826
00:53:12,355 --> 00:53:16,443
Now, it's not like regular ice.
You can't touch it with your hands, okay?

827
00:53:16,568 --> 00:53:19,946
[Jack] Second, he's really smart.

828
00:53:20,030 --> 00:53:22,866
He's ahead of me in everything.

829
00:53:22,949 --> 00:53:25,744
In science, 
he's ahead of the whole school.

830
00:53:25,827 --> 00:53:27,203
Everybody watching?

831
00:53:27,871 --> 00:53:30,123
-Whoo!
-[all laugh]

832
00:53:30,206 --> 00:53:34,002
[Jack] Third of all,
he's actually pretty funny.

833
00:53:34,753 --> 00:53:37,505
But fourthly, now that I know him,

834
00:53:37,589 --> 00:53:40,759
I would say I actually 
do wanna be friends with Auggie.

835
00:53:40,842 --> 00:53:42,969
At first, I admit it,

836
00:53:43,053 --> 00:53:46,389
I was only friendly to him because
my mom asked me to be nice.

837
00:53:47,974 --> 00:53:51,853
But now I would choose
to hang out with him.

838
00:53:51,937 --> 00:53:53,813
Like, he's a good friend.

839
00:53:54,439 --> 00:53:57,484
Like if all the guys in fifth grade
were lined up against a wall

840
00:53:57,567 --> 00:54:02,072
and I could choose anyone I wanted 
to hang out with, I would choose Auggie.

841
00:54:04,908 --> 00:54:06,451
Hey, what's wrong?

842
00:54:06,576 --> 00:54:08,036
Go away.

843
00:54:08,578 --> 00:54:10,830
[Julian] Oh, hey, Jack, come sit with us.

844
00:54:10,914 --> 00:54:12,248
Yeah, come on, man.

845
00:54:17,003 --> 00:54:18,171
I wonder what happened.

846
00:54:18,296 --> 00:54:20,465
[Ximena] Maybe Jack touched Auggie
and couldn't wash his hands in time.

847
00:54:20,590 --> 00:54:22,008
Jack finally got "the plague."

848
00:54:22,092 --> 00:54:24,344
[Charlotte] That's not very nice.

849
00:54:24,469 --> 00:54:26,304
What? We didn't start it.

850
00:54:26,388 --> 00:54:28,139
Where are you going?

851
00:54:35,355 --> 00:54:37,565
Hi. I'm Summer.

852
00:54:37,941 --> 00:54:39,985
I know. We're in the same homeroom.

853
00:54:40,902 --> 00:54:42,487
You don't have to do this.

854
00:54:42,570 --> 00:54:43,905
Do what?

855
00:54:44,781 --> 00:54:46,199
You don't have to be my friend.

856
00:54:46,282 --> 00:54:48,076
I know Tushman talked to you.

857
00:54:48,159 --> 00:54:50,078
I don't know
what you're talking about, Auggie.

858
00:54:50,161 --> 00:54:53,206
I know Tushman talked to some kids
before school started

859
00:54:53,289 --> 00:54:55,291
and told them
they had to be friends with me.

860
00:54:55,375 --> 00:54:56,960
He didn't talk to me.

861
00:54:57,043 --> 00:54:58,294
Yeah, he did.

862
00:54:58,378 --> 00:54:59,879
No, he did not.

863
00:54:59,963 --> 00:55:00,880
Yeah, he did.

864
00:55:00,964 --> 00:55:02,382
No, he didn't, I swear on my life!

865
00:55:02,507 --> 00:55:05,969
[Auggie] Okay, okay.
You don't have to get mad.

866
00:55:06,052 --> 00:55:08,638
I don't like
being accused of things, okay?

867
00:55:08,722 --> 00:55:10,265
Okay. I'm sorry.

868
00:55:10,348 --> 00:55:11,599
You should be.

869
00:55:13,810 --> 00:55:15,937
-He really didn't talk to you?
-Auggie!

870
00:55:16,021 --> 00:55:18,690
Okay, I just...
Why are you sitting here then?

871
00:55:20,859 --> 00:55:23,069
Because I want some nice friends
for a change.

872
00:55:23,945 --> 00:55:25,196
Me too.

873
00:55:25,280 --> 00:55:26,656
Cool beans.

874
00:55:27,949 --> 00:55:29,576
But you'll get "the plague."

875
00:55:30,326 --> 00:55:31,453
Good.

876
00:55:34,873 --> 00:55:36,082
Summer has "the plague."

877
00:55:36,791 --> 00:55:38,043
Shut up!

878
00:55:41,087 --> 00:55:42,839
So what happened with Jack Will?

879
00:55:44,007 --> 00:55:45,175
Promise you won't tell?

880
00:55:49,846 --> 00:55:51,222
I got it! I got the part!

881
00:55:51,306 --> 00:55:53,058
-Congratulations.
-Thank you. [laughs]

882
00:55:56,019 --> 00:55:58,521
[mimicking]
She got it! She got the part! Oh, my God!

883
00:55:58,605 --> 00:55:59,731
Bet she got Emily.

884
00:55:59,814 --> 00:56:01,608
-Yep.
-[sighs]

885
00:56:01,691 --> 00:56:02,734
What'd you get?

886
00:56:03,860 --> 00:56:05,445
Emily's understudy.

887
00:56:06,529 --> 00:56:10,950
I'm not saying poison or anything,
but just a little Benadryl

888
00:56:11,034 --> 00:56:12,410
-to knock Miranda out before the show.
-[laughs]

889
00:56:12,494 --> 00:56:14,621
Okay, enough.

890
00:56:14,704 --> 00:56:16,706
Look, just learn her lines

891
00:56:16,790 --> 00:56:19,459
and it'll give us
an excuse to hang out more.

892
00:56:19,542 --> 00:56:22,670
We can start rehearsing the kissing scene
on Page 110.

893
00:56:23,755 --> 00:56:26,216
Wait. George and Emily?

894
00:56:30,720 --> 00:56:32,931
There is no Page 110.

895
00:56:35,016 --> 00:56:39,646
So I'm thinking,
I really wanna kiss you right now.

896
00:56:39,729 --> 00:56:41,773
But I don't know how you'll respond.

897
00:56:59,541 --> 00:57:00,708
What's wrong?

898
00:57:05,046 --> 00:57:06,673
I'm not an only child.

899
00:57:11,052 --> 00:57:12,053
Mom?

900
00:57:12,137 --> 00:57:14,597
One sec, Via. Auggie, let's go!

901
00:57:18,434 --> 00:57:20,228
I thought you were at the library.

902
00:57:21,312 --> 00:57:22,897
Uh, um...

903
00:57:22,981 --> 00:57:24,232
Yeah, change of plans.

904
00:57:24,315 --> 00:57:25,442
Mmm-hmm.

905
00:57:26,234 --> 00:57:27,610
Hi, I'm Justin.

906
00:57:27,694 --> 00:57:29,112
-I'm Isabel.
-[door opens]

907
00:57:31,114 --> 00:57:33,324
Daisy threw up again. Bucket loads.

908
00:57:35,285 --> 00:57:36,536
[Isabel] Bucket loads.

909
00:57:39,122 --> 00:57:41,958
[Via] Um, Justin, this is
my little brother Auggie.

910
00:57:43,293 --> 00:57:45,545
-Hey, dude!
-[Auggie] Hey.

911
00:57:46,379 --> 00:57:48,840
What's that in your case? A machine gun?

912
00:57:49,799 --> 00:57:51,301
[laughs]

913
00:57:51,384 --> 00:57:54,554
Er, no. It's a fiddle.

914
00:57:54,637 --> 00:57:56,055
You should tell people it's a machine gun.

915
00:57:56,139 --> 00:57:58,016
That's way cooler.

916
00:57:58,975 --> 00:58:00,059
You know what?

917
00:58:00,143 --> 00:58:01,936
That's a great idea, you're right.

918
00:58:02,020 --> 00:58:03,521
We're on our way to the grocery.

919
00:58:03,605 --> 00:58:06,107
-Mom's making-- What's it called?
-Feijoada.

920
00:58:06,191 --> 00:58:08,443
-Mom's making feijoada.
-It's Dad's favourite.

921
00:58:08,526 --> 00:58:10,403
You're welcome to stay
if you want, Justin.

922
00:58:10,487 --> 00:58:13,072
Oh, thank you very much.
It was nice meeting you.

923
00:58:13,156 --> 00:58:14,073
[Isabel] Nice to meet you, too.

924
00:58:18,453 --> 00:58:20,205
Psst. Oy! [snaps fingers]

925
00:58:20,288 --> 00:58:21,372
Bye, Auggie.

926
00:58:21,581 --> 00:58:23,374
Nothing to see here.

927
00:58:24,667 --> 00:58:27,420
[door opens and closes]

928
00:58:29,589 --> 00:58:33,968
It's a gene. Well, it's sort of two genes,
but two genes that are identical.

929
00:58:34,052 --> 00:58:36,137
And the trouble is that both of my parents

930
00:58:36,221 --> 00:58:38,765
carry the gene at the same time,
which is...

931
00:58:38,848 --> 00:58:41,768
Well essentially, he won the lottery.

932
00:58:41,851 --> 00:58:43,478
Backwards or something.

933
00:58:43,728 --> 00:58:48,858
And in another world, I'd look like him.

934
00:58:53,821 --> 00:58:56,199
I'm sorry for telling you
that I was an only child.

935
00:58:58,284 --> 00:59:00,870
Sometimes it's nice to hide a little.

936
00:59:02,038 --> 00:59:03,998
I get it. It's okay.

937
00:59:14,175 --> 00:59:15,843
[Via laughing]

938
00:59:34,529 --> 00:59:36,572
[phone ringing]

939
00:59:38,866 --> 00:59:39,701
Hello?

940
00:59:39,784 --> 00:59:41,327
[Miranda on phone] Major Tom, is that you?

941
00:59:41,411 --> 00:59:42,495
Miranda!

942
00:59:42,579 --> 00:59:44,998
[Miranda]
It's so great to hear your voice again.

943
00:59:45,665 --> 00:59:47,542
Sorry, Via's not here.

944
00:59:48,042 --> 00:59:50,878
[Miranda] I was actually calling
to say hello to you.

945
00:59:50,962 --> 00:59:51,879
How have you been?

946
00:59:52,171 --> 00:59:54,757
Good. Did you know I'm going
to a regular school now?

947
00:59:54,841 --> 00:59:55,675
[Miranda] No way.

948
00:59:56,426 --> 00:59:57,427
Do you like it?

949
00:59:58,052 --> 00:59:59,512
[Auggie] Yeah, I guess.

950
00:59:59,596 --> 01:00:01,264
It's not as hard as Mom's homeschool.

951
01:00:01,723 --> 01:00:03,224
[chuckles] Yeah, I'll bet.

952
01:00:04,601 --> 01:00:06,352
How are the kids? Are they nice?

953
01:00:06,811 --> 01:00:09,188
[Auggie] No. But I made one friend.

954
01:00:09,647 --> 01:00:10,481
Her name's Summer.

955
01:00:10,898 --> 01:00:12,525
We started a summer names club.

956
01:00:13,067 --> 01:00:16,029
-Summer, August. Get it?
-[chuckles]

957
01:00:16,112 --> 01:00:17,614
Good for you, Auggie. [chuckles]

958
01:00:19,532 --> 01:00:22,201
Um, where's Via, anyway?

959
01:00:22,619 --> 01:00:23,911
[Auggie] She's out with her boyfriend.

960
01:00:25,371 --> 01:00:26,956
Really?

961
01:00:27,040 --> 01:00:29,917
[Auggie] Yeah. We met him last week.
He's super nice.

962
01:00:35,131 --> 01:00:36,507
I've missed you, Major Tom.

963
01:00:37,675 --> 01:00:38,968
[Auggie] I miss you too, Miranda.

964
01:00:41,471 --> 01:00:44,307
And can you tell Via
that I've missed her, too?

965
01:00:44,682 --> 01:00:47,352
[Auggie] Well, 
but why don't you just tell her yourself?

966
01:00:50,104 --> 01:00:53,900
Listen, I gotta go,
my mom's calling me, but, um,

967
01:00:53,983 --> 01:00:56,152
you know that you can call me
any time, right?

968
01:00:56,235 --> 01:00:57,236
[Auggie] Yeah.

969
01:00:59,530 --> 01:01:01,866
Okay, so call me any time.

970
01:01:01,949 --> 01:01:03,284
I will.

971
01:01:03,368 --> 01:01:04,577
Merry Christmas, Auggie.

972
01:01:05,703 --> 01:01:06,996
Merry Christmas, Miranda.

973
01:01:26,557 --> 01:01:28,017
[lift dings]

974
01:01:31,062 --> 01:01:32,939
-[Nate] Get after it.
-Open it. Rip it apart.

975
01:01:33,022 --> 01:01:35,942
[Miranda] Via and I have been best friends
since kindergarten.

976
01:01:36,025 --> 01:01:37,652
Oh, my God!

977
01:01:37,735 --> 01:01:40,738
[Miranda] Her family's always been 
like my second family.

978
01:01:40,822 --> 01:01:42,657
Auggie's always felt
like my little brother.

979
01:01:42,740 --> 01:01:44,242
-[all laugh]
-How does it feel?

980
01:01:44,701 --> 01:01:46,411
-Awesome.
-Good.

981
01:01:46,494 --> 01:01:50,373
[Miranda] And for a few years even our
family's spent Christmas together.

982
01:01:50,456 --> 01:01:52,291
[Isabel] Everybody say "Merry Christmas"!

983
01:01:52,375 --> 01:01:54,502
[all] Merry Christmas!

984
01:01:56,879 --> 01:01:59,590
[Miranda] But now my dad's busy
with his new wife.

985
01:02:00,091 --> 01:02:01,551
Who was his old boss.

986
01:02:03,553 --> 01:02:07,432
And my mom, well, 
she's busy not getting over that.

987
01:02:11,519 --> 01:02:13,396
I got a job at a summer camp.

988
01:02:13,688 --> 01:02:16,023
Just so I'd have somewhere
to go that wasn't home.

989
01:02:18,484 --> 01:02:22,697
One day, and I swear
I didn't plan this, but...

990
01:02:22,780 --> 01:02:27,493
I started playing this little make
believe game with the girls in the camp.

991
01:02:29,370 --> 01:02:32,373
I said I lived in a huge brownstone.

992
01:02:32,457 --> 01:02:34,250
On a nice street.

993
01:02:34,333 --> 01:02:36,711
With my two awesome parents.

994
01:02:37,879 --> 01:02:39,922
And my awesome dog named Daisy.

995
01:02:40,965 --> 01:02:45,219
And my awesome little brother
with a facial deformity.

996
01:02:48,181 --> 01:02:50,683
And, oh, my God, everyone went crazy.

997
01:02:50,766 --> 01:02:52,393
"What do you mean, deformity?

998
01:02:52,643 --> 01:02:53,853
What does he look like?"

999
01:02:55,313 --> 01:02:57,773
Suddenly, everyone wanted to talk to me.

1000
01:02:57,857 --> 01:03:02,236
And by the end of summer, 
I was the most popular girl in camp.

1001
01:03:04,197 --> 01:03:07,074
When I got home, I wanted to call Via.

1002
01:03:07,158 --> 01:03:11,245
But she would've asked me about
my parents and about camp.

1003
01:03:12,580 --> 01:03:15,583
And then I saw Via audition for the play.

1004
01:03:15,666 --> 01:03:18,127
And I remembered how cool she is.

1005
01:03:19,212 --> 01:03:24,217
And how I understood why everyone in camp
loved me more when I pretended to be her.

1006
01:03:26,385 --> 01:03:28,513
She used to let Auggie
hang out with us all the time.

1007
01:03:30,223 --> 01:03:32,850
I was the one who bought him
his astronaut helmet.

1008
01:03:34,727 --> 01:03:36,771
He was so into outer space.

1009
01:03:38,064 --> 01:03:40,858
And I wanted him to know that 
the world was bigger than his room.

1010
01:03:43,194 --> 01:03:47,365
And now he's out there.
And I didn't even know.

1011
01:03:49,450 --> 01:03:50,535
I could've helped him.

1012
01:03:52,161 --> 01:03:53,871
Maybe he could've helped me.

1013
01:03:55,706 --> 01:03:56,666
I don't know.

1014
01:03:58,626 --> 01:04:00,378
But I could sure use some help right now.

1015
01:04:01,003 --> 01:04:03,214
[indistinct conversation and laughter]

1016
01:04:23,568 --> 01:04:25,403
[Summer and Auggie whooping]

1017
01:04:27,530 --> 01:04:28,364
[laughing]

1018
01:04:34,328 --> 01:04:36,414
That was awesome!

1019
01:04:36,539 --> 01:04:37,582
[chuckles]

1020
01:04:38,583 --> 01:04:40,501
Hey, look, there's Jack Will.

1021
01:04:44,672 --> 01:04:46,299
Let's find another hill.

1022
01:04:47,508 --> 01:04:49,719
You can't just
keep avoiding him forever, Auggie.

1023
01:04:49,802 --> 01:04:50,928
Come on, let's go!

1024
01:05:13,409 --> 01:05:19,165
[crowd chanting] Nine. Eight. Seven.
Six. Five. Four.

1025
01:05:19,498 --> 01:05:23,753
Three. Two. One. Happy New Year!

1026
01:05:23,836 --> 01:05:25,880
[all cheering]

1027
01:05:25,963 --> 01:05:28,591
-Happy New Year!
-Happy New Year!

1028
01:05:46,317 --> 01:05:48,402
[grunting]

1029
01:05:53,366 --> 01:05:57,119
Thanks for the help, Daisy.
Way to put your back into it.

1030
01:06:06,045 --> 01:06:07,588
[Miles] What about you?

1031
01:06:08,047 --> 01:06:10,549
Christmas was awesome.
We drove up into the mountains

1032
01:06:10,633 --> 01:06:13,052
where they had the most
amazing snow I've ever seen.

1033
01:06:13,135 --> 01:06:14,637
-It was like powder.
-Nice.

1034
01:06:14,720 --> 01:06:15,721
What about you, Jack?

1035
01:06:15,930 --> 01:06:18,849
I went up Skeleton Hill. It was the best.

1036
01:06:18,933 --> 01:06:19,976
[Amos] Skeleton Hill?

1037
01:06:20,059 --> 01:06:21,102
I hate that place!

1038
01:06:21,185 --> 01:06:22,603
Should be called Garbage Hill.

1039
01:06:22,687 --> 01:06:23,562
I know, right?

1040
01:06:23,646 --> 01:06:26,148
I left my old lightning sled there
last time I was up.

1041
01:06:26,816 --> 01:06:28,901
It was the crappiest piece of junk.

1042
01:06:29,610 --> 01:06:31,278
Went back the next day
and someone had taken it.

1043
01:06:31,362 --> 01:06:33,072
[Julian] Hey, maybe a homeless guy
wanted to go sledding.

1044
01:06:33,155 --> 01:06:34,907
[Miles and Amos] Yeah.

1045
01:06:35,366 --> 01:06:36,450
[Mr Browne] New precept.

1046
01:06:36,534 --> 01:06:38,911
Your deeds are your monuments.

1047
01:06:39,203 --> 01:06:40,996
Archaeologists found these words inscribed

1048
01:06:41,080 --> 01:06:43,290
on the walls of an ancient Egyptian tomb.

1049
01:06:43,374 --> 01:06:44,834
Can anybody tell me what they mean?

1050
01:06:47,044 --> 01:06:48,129
Summer?

1051
01:06:48,879 --> 01:06:50,214
Oh, uh...

1052
01:06:52,258 --> 01:06:55,511
I think it means that the things we do
are the things that matter most.

1053
01:06:56,178 --> 01:06:58,723
[Mr Browne] Excellent. Anybody else?

1054
01:07:02,268 --> 01:07:03,477
Hey, Summer?

1055
01:07:04,979 --> 01:07:06,731
Hey. You okay?

1056
01:07:07,398 --> 01:07:09,859
Yeah. Fine. Just...

1057
01:07:11,027 --> 01:07:13,195
This is gonna sound stupid, but,

1058
01:07:14,613 --> 01:07:16,657
do you know why Auggie stopped liking me?

1059
01:07:17,533 --> 01:07:19,076
You should ask him.

1060
01:07:19,160 --> 01:07:23,539
I have, but ever since Halloween,
he just won't talk to me.

1061
01:07:24,415 --> 01:07:27,835
I mean... You know what?
I don't care. Sorry.

1062
01:07:27,918 --> 01:07:29,253
Ghostface.

1063
01:07:31,505 --> 01:07:32,506
Wait, wait, what?

1064
01:07:33,340 --> 01:07:34,717
That's all I can tell you.

1065
01:07:39,680 --> 01:07:40,639
Okay.

1066
01:07:40,723 --> 01:07:42,475
Now that we've finished our tests,

1067
01:07:42,558 --> 01:07:46,771
I want you all to start thinking about
our fifth grade science fair projects.

1068
01:07:46,854 --> 01:07:50,691
Which you will need to work on
to have ready after spring break.

1069
01:07:50,775 --> 01:07:54,111
Okay? Now, it could be about anything.

1070
01:07:54,195 --> 01:07:55,237
[voice fades]

1071
01:07:55,362 --> 01:07:57,198
[inaudible]

1072
01:08:07,875 --> 01:08:11,712
[Ms Petosa] The point is to create
something you're excited about.

1073
01:08:11,796 --> 01:08:13,631
Something you're proud to show.

1074
01:08:14,131 --> 01:08:15,216
Mr Will?

1075
01:08:16,717 --> 01:08:17,593
Mr Will?

1076
01:08:19,011 --> 01:08:20,721
Something more important to think about?

1077
01:08:21,055 --> 01:08:22,056
No.

1078
01:08:22,139 --> 01:08:24,183
So, it'll be teams of two.

1079
01:08:24,266 --> 01:08:26,435
Your partner will be your tablemate.

1080
01:08:27,603 --> 01:08:28,562
[Julian] Uh, Ms Petosa?

1081
01:08:29,355 --> 01:08:30,856
I know we're supposed to be in pairs,

1082
01:08:30,940 --> 01:08:33,651
but Jack, Amos and I
had this science fair project idea

1083
01:08:33,734 --> 01:08:35,152
that we wanted to work on together.

1084
01:08:35,236 --> 01:08:36,195
[Ms Petosa] Okay, maybe we can switch.

1085
01:08:36,278 --> 01:08:37,321
Uh, no.

1086
01:08:37,863 --> 01:08:38,697
Sorry?

1087
01:08:38,781 --> 01:08:39,824
What?

1088
01:08:39,907 --> 01:08:44,203
No, um, it's... It's okay.
I'll stay with who I've got.

1089
01:08:45,788 --> 01:08:46,664
I'll stick with Auggie.

1090
01:08:51,794 --> 01:08:53,879
Hey! What did you do that for?

1091
01:08:53,963 --> 01:08:55,673
Dude, I don't want to switch.

1092
01:08:55,756 --> 01:08:59,009
Why not? Do you really
wanna be partners with that freak?

1093
01:09:05,766 --> 01:09:07,309
[inaudible]

1094
01:09:07,935 --> 01:09:12,064
[Jack] Dear Mr Tushman, 
I'm very sorry for punching Julian.

1095
01:09:12,148 --> 01:09:13,816
It was wrong of me to do that.

1096
01:09:14,441 --> 01:09:16,318
I know you may need to expel me,

1097
01:09:16,402 --> 01:09:22,324
but I'd still rather not say
why I did what I did.

1098
01:09:22,449 --> 01:09:24,702
It might get Julian in trouble, too,

1099
01:09:24,785 --> 01:09:26,745
-and that's not fair.
-Stop!

1100
01:09:27,454 --> 01:09:29,248
Sincerely, Jack Will.

1101
01:09:31,250 --> 01:09:36,547
[Mr Tushman] Dear Mr Will, one thing
I've learned in 20 years in education

1102
01:09:37,339 --> 01:09:39,925
is that there are two sides
to every story.

1103
01:09:40,885 --> 01:09:44,221
So I think I can imagine
what started the fight.

1104
01:09:45,973 --> 01:09:49,143
While nothing justifies
striking another student,

1105
01:09:50,311 --> 01:09:52,938
I know good friends are worth defending.

1106
01:09:54,148 --> 01:09:56,942
So, after your two-day suspension

1107
01:09:58,319 --> 01:09:59,945
your scholarship will be waiting for you.

1108
01:10:01,989 --> 01:10:03,616
Just keep up the good work.

1109
01:10:03,699 --> 01:10:06,285
And keep being the fine boy
we all know you to be.

1110
01:10:07,369 --> 01:10:10,247
Sincerely, Mr Tushman.

1111
01:10:15,628 --> 01:10:17,838
[Via] What's so wrong with me
not telling you about a stupid play?

1112
01:10:17,922 --> 01:10:20,090
I'm not even in it.
I'm just doing the lights.

1113
01:10:20,174 --> 01:10:21,008
Well, your boyfriend is in it.

1114
01:10:21,091 --> 01:10:22,927
And don't you think
we would like to see him?

1115
01:10:23,010 --> 01:10:23,886
No, I don't!

1116
01:10:23,969 --> 01:10:25,596
Look, let's all calm down for a second.

1117
01:10:25,679 --> 01:10:28,599
You know, you've been really good
at leaving me alone my whole life.

1118
01:10:29,308 --> 01:10:31,352
So why are you suddenly
so interested, huh?

1119
01:10:31,435 --> 01:10:34,063
Are... Are you bored
now that Auggie's in school?

1120
01:10:34,146 --> 01:10:36,065
Your thesis not going well?

1121
01:10:36,148 --> 01:10:37,900
Nate, could you please excuse us?

1122
01:10:37,983 --> 01:10:39,026
-Izzy, she doesn't mean it.
-Nate!

1123
01:10:44,281 --> 01:10:46,075
[Isabel arguing indistinctly]

1124
01:10:46,158 --> 01:10:47,910
What are they saying down there?

1125
01:10:47,993 --> 01:10:50,829
[Nate] They, my friend,
are saying a lot of things.

1126
01:10:50,913 --> 01:10:53,123
None of which concern us.

1127
01:10:53,207 --> 01:10:55,376
Let's see your new Minecraft world.

1128
01:10:55,459 --> 01:10:57,711
'Cause we might be moving to it.

1129
01:11:08,889 --> 01:11:12,101
So, are we going to see the play?

1130
01:11:12,977 --> 01:11:14,061
Um...

1131
01:11:14,144 --> 01:11:17,147
I hadn't realized what the play was

1132
01:11:17,231 --> 01:11:20,901
and I don't think it will be of
any interest to a kid your age.

1133
01:11:21,068 --> 01:11:23,487
Yeah, uh, you'd get totally bored.

1134
01:11:25,155 --> 01:11:26,824
[Auggie] Are you and Dad going?

1135
01:11:26,907 --> 01:11:29,827
Daddy'll go.
And I'm gonna stay here with you.

1136
01:11:29,910 --> 01:11:31,662
What?

1137
01:11:31,745 --> 01:11:33,706
So now you're gonna punish me
by not going?

1138
01:11:34,248 --> 01:11:37,042
Well, you didn't want me to go
in the first place, remember?

1139
01:11:37,126 --> 01:11:40,045
Well, now that you know about it,
of course I want you to come.

1140
01:11:40,921 --> 01:11:42,089
What are you talking about?

1141
01:11:42,214 --> 01:11:43,257
-Nothing.
-[Via] Nothing.

1142
01:11:48,095 --> 01:11:49,096
You're lying.

1143
01:11:49,221 --> 01:11:51,765
It's just something to do
with Via's school, honey.

1144
01:11:51,849 --> 01:11:54,059
You just don't want your
fancy high school friends

1145
01:11:54,143 --> 01:11:55,352
to know your brother's a freak, huh?

1146
01:11:55,436 --> 01:11:57,313
-[Isabel] Auggie!
-Auggie, that's not true.

1147
01:11:57,396 --> 01:12:00,357
Stop lying to me, I'm not an idiot,
I know what's going on!

1148
01:12:04,570 --> 01:12:06,322
[Daisy whimpering]

1149
01:12:10,284 --> 01:12:11,869
Daisy girl?

1150
01:12:12,453 --> 01:12:14,872
Auggie. Come on.

1151
01:12:14,955 --> 01:12:16,040
[Auggie] It's okay, I don't wanna go

1152
01:12:16,123 --> 01:12:18,333
to your stupid high school anyway.
I don't care.

1153
01:12:18,417 --> 01:12:21,253
Auggie, not everything
in the world is about you.

1154
01:12:21,337 --> 01:12:22,421
[Via sniffles]

1155
01:12:22,504 --> 01:12:23,630
What's wrong?

1156
01:12:26,091 --> 01:12:27,593
[Daisy whimpers]

1157
01:12:35,142 --> 01:12:36,268
[Daisy whimpering]

1158
01:12:38,479 --> 01:12:39,938
You're gonna be fine, girlie.

1159
01:12:40,022 --> 01:12:42,399
Daddy's gonna meet me there.
Take care of your brother.

1160
01:12:42,483 --> 01:12:43,442
[Via] Yeah.

1161
01:12:43,525 --> 01:12:45,569
Okay. All right.

1162
01:13:03,170 --> 01:13:04,588
Did Daisy really bite Mom?

1163
01:13:05,881 --> 01:13:09,718
Well, um, she was whimpering.

1164
01:13:10,469 --> 01:13:13,347
And then Mom tried to pick her up
and Daisy bit her.

1165
01:13:14,848 --> 01:13:16,809
Do you think the vet can fix her?

1166
01:13:19,061 --> 01:13:21,355
She was in a lot of pain, Auggie.

1167
01:13:23,482 --> 01:13:25,067
She's really old.

1168
01:13:29,780 --> 01:13:30,823
Auggie?

1169
01:13:32,741 --> 01:13:35,702
I want you to come to my play. Okay?

1170
01:13:37,454 --> 01:13:38,330
Really?

1171
01:13:39,331 --> 01:13:40,457
Really.

1172
01:13:45,879 --> 01:13:47,256
[door opens]

1173
01:14:29,923 --> 01:14:31,300
[crying]

1174
01:14:42,478 --> 01:14:43,937
[sniffles]

1175
01:14:54,615 --> 01:14:59,161
[Auggie] Every time I came home
from the hospital, Daisy was here.

1176
01:15:02,456 --> 01:15:04,166
She was a real friend.

1177
01:15:06,210 --> 01:15:10,130
And real friends are hard to find.

1178
01:15:14,468 --> 01:15:15,469
[beeps]

1179
01:16:18,824 --> 01:16:20,242
[laughs]

1180
01:16:58,405 --> 01:16:59,406
Excuse me.

1181
01:16:59,489 --> 01:17:02,409
Sorry. Thank you.

1182
01:17:06,246 --> 01:17:09,166
-This is perfect.
-Here we go. Good seats.

1183
01:17:09,249 --> 01:17:11,376
Here. See if you can find
Via's name in there, honey.

1184
01:17:13,045 --> 01:17:16,757
Glasses. Oh, no! [gasps]
I think I forgot my glasses.

1185
01:17:17,716 --> 01:17:20,677
Auggie, you're missing
a great episode of Hoarders right here.

1186
01:17:21,303 --> 01:17:22,929
-Starring your mom's purse.
-[chuckles]

1187
01:17:26,975 --> 01:17:28,143
You ready?

1188
01:17:28,226 --> 01:17:30,312
Are you supposed to be
in the girls' dressing room?

1189
01:17:30,395 --> 01:17:31,646
Just wanted to wish you good luck.

1190
01:17:32,230 --> 01:17:33,649
"Break a leg," not "Good luck."

1191
01:17:34,399 --> 01:17:35,400
You too.

1192
01:17:36,777 --> 01:17:38,320
Anyone cheering you on tonight?

1193
01:17:39,488 --> 01:17:43,158
Uh, yeah, my mom invited

1194
01:17:43,241 --> 01:17:45,160
-the entire block.
-[chuckles]

1195
01:17:45,243 --> 01:17:46,703
It's gonna be really embarrassing.

1196
01:17:46,787 --> 01:17:48,997
-[both chuckle]
-You?

1197
01:17:49,831 --> 01:17:52,793
Uh, my dad is on his belated honeymoon.

1198
01:17:52,876 --> 01:17:54,252
And my mom's in a funk.

1199
01:17:54,336 --> 01:17:56,338
But maybe she'll come tomorrow.

1200
01:17:59,257 --> 01:18:02,010
Well, um, Via's family will cheer you on.

1201
01:18:04,262 --> 01:18:05,472
You'll be great tonight.

1202
01:18:16,483 --> 01:18:19,736
-[softly] Honey, just enjoy the play.
-Okay.

1203
01:18:23,657 --> 01:18:24,658
All right, go get 'em.

1204
01:18:26,326 --> 01:18:27,327
-Mr Davenport...
-Hmm.

1205
01:18:27,411 --> 01:18:29,579
I'm really sorry,
but I can't go on tonight.

1206
01:18:29,663 --> 01:18:31,373
I don't feel well.
I think I might throw up.

1207
01:18:31,456 --> 01:18:32,666
Okay, everybody gets nervous.

1208
01:18:32,749 --> 01:18:33,750
You know, when I did my Hamlet,

1209
01:18:33,834 --> 01:18:35,585
I threw up every night.
You're gonna be fine.

1210
01:18:35,669 --> 01:18:37,587
Just do it. You'll have
all of spring break to recover.

1211
01:18:37,671 --> 01:18:40,173
Mr Davenport, you're not listening.
I'm not going on.

1212
01:18:44,302 --> 01:18:45,178
Are you kidding me?

1213
01:18:46,138 --> 01:18:49,057
I'm really sorry, but Via
knows all the lines. She can do it.

1214
01:18:50,684 --> 01:18:52,519
Then go find her, then.

1215
01:18:53,437 --> 01:18:54,438
Thank you.

1216
01:18:55,856 --> 01:18:57,190
[exhales]

1217
01:18:58,316 --> 01:19:00,277
-Hi.
-Hi.

1218
01:19:04,364 --> 01:19:06,366
[mellow instrumental music playing]

1219
01:19:10,579 --> 01:19:13,331
This play is called Our Town.

1220
01:19:13,415 --> 01:19:15,625
It was written by Thornton Wilder.

1221
01:19:16,543 --> 01:19:20,881
The name of our town
is Grover's Corners, New Hampshire.

1222
01:19:21,756 --> 01:19:23,925
Just across the Massachusetts line.

1223
01:19:24,009 --> 01:19:25,469
Is this... Is this really happening?

1224
01:19:25,552 --> 01:19:28,138
Yes, you're going on as Emily.
Only you don't have much time.

1225
01:19:28,221 --> 01:19:30,557
Well, I don't even know
if I'm gonna remember all of my lines.

1226
01:19:30,640 --> 01:19:32,350
You'll be great.
Justin will help you through it.

1227
01:19:32,434 --> 01:19:33,268
[Mr Davenport] Where is she?

1228
01:19:34,227 --> 01:19:35,562
Via, you're on in two minutes.

1229
01:19:35,645 --> 01:19:37,522
Why, why are you doing this?

1230
01:19:37,606 --> 01:19:40,192
I told you. I feel sick.

1231
01:19:41,401 --> 01:19:45,864
We've got a factory in our town, too.
You hear it?

1232
01:19:46,448 --> 01:19:49,451
-Hey, it's okay. Hey, break a leg.
-[Justin] Makes blankets.

1233
01:19:49,534 --> 01:19:52,537
Cartwrights own it
and it brung 'em a fortune.

1234
01:19:57,417 --> 01:19:59,294
[Mrs Webb] Children, now I won't have it.

1235
01:19:59,377 --> 01:20:01,505
Breakfast is just as good
as any other meal.

1236
01:20:01,588 --> 01:20:03,673
And I won't have you gobbling like wolves.

1237
01:20:03,757 --> 01:20:05,217
It'll stunt your growth. That's a fact.

1238
01:20:05,842 --> 01:20:07,761
[whispers] Miranda looks so different.

1239
01:20:07,844 --> 01:20:10,347
[whispers] That's not Miranda, it's Via.

1240
01:20:10,430 --> 01:20:12,557
-What?
-It's Via.

1241
01:20:13,391 --> 01:20:14,226
Oh, great.

1242
01:20:15,769 --> 01:20:19,439
[Mrs Webb] As for me, I'd rather have
my children healthy than bright.

1243
01:20:19,731 --> 01:20:22,150
I'm both, Mama, you know I am.

1244
01:20:23,193 --> 01:20:25,278
I'm the brightest girl
in school for my age.

1245
01:20:25,362 --> 01:20:27,280
I have a wonderful memory.

1246
01:20:27,364 --> 01:20:28,949
[Mrs Webb] Eat your breakfast.

1247
01:20:32,327 --> 01:20:33,954
[play continues indistinctly]

1248
01:20:36,623 --> 01:20:39,543
Hmm. Your stomach flu got better fast.

1249
01:20:40,335 --> 01:20:41,962
Sorry, sir, just jitters.

1250
01:20:42,045 --> 01:20:44,339
I'll be ready by tomorrow night.

1251
01:20:44,422 --> 01:20:46,299
She's doing very well.

1252
01:20:52,556 --> 01:20:55,976
I can't. I can't go on.

1253
01:20:59,813 --> 01:21:01,815
It... it goes so fast.

1254
01:21:02,440 --> 01:21:04,442
We don't even have time
to look at one another.

1255
01:21:05,819 --> 01:21:07,362
I didn't realize.

1256
01:21:07,445 --> 01:21:09,990
So all that was going on
and we never noticed?

1257
01:21:13,076 --> 01:21:17,289
Take me back. Up the hill. To my grave.

1258
01:21:18,957 --> 01:21:23,795
But first, wait, one more look.

1259
01:21:27,007 --> 01:21:30,594
Goodbye. Goodbye, world.

1260
01:21:33,013 --> 01:21:34,723
Goodbye, Grover's Corners.

1261
01:21:36,516 --> 01:21:37,517
Mama.

