1510
01:37:33,013 --> 01:37:34,598
[crying]

1511
01:37:47,361 --> 01:37:50,322
-[fireworks bursting]
-[kids cheering]

1512
01:38:18,642 --> 01:38:20,019
[Isabel] Hi!

1513
01:38:20,102 --> 01:38:23,355
Oh, my gosh, I missed you so much! Mmm.

1514
01:38:23,439 --> 01:38:25,316
-See you later, Auggie!
-[Auggie] Bye!

1515
01:38:25,399 --> 01:38:26,275
How are you?

1516
01:38:26,358 --> 01:38:28,110
Good. And guess what? I got in a fight.

1517
01:38:28,193 --> 01:38:30,779
[gasps] Oh, my God, you're bleeding!
Are you okay?

1518
01:38:30,863 --> 01:38:31,864
What happened?

1519
01:38:31,947 --> 01:38:33,490
[Isabel] Auggie got in a fight.

1520
01:38:34,867 --> 01:38:36,535
[Nate] That's terrible. I'm sorry.

1521
01:38:36,619 --> 01:38:38,871
-Did you win?
-Nate!

1522
01:38:38,954 --> 01:38:41,707
Well, I'm getting a vibe
like maybe he won.

1523
01:38:42,541 --> 01:38:43,626
Did you?

1524
01:38:43,709 --> 01:38:47,087
Yeah. And guess what?
They were seventh graders.

1525
01:38:47,171 --> 01:38:49,089
-[mimics explosion]
-Yes!

1526
01:38:49,173 --> 01:38:50,549
[Miles] See you later, buddy!

1527
01:38:50,633 --> 01:38:51,467
Bye!

1528
01:38:53,552 --> 01:38:55,095
[Nate] Fighting is bad, Auggie.

1529
01:38:55,179 --> 01:38:57,640
-Bye, Mr and Mrs P.
-[Nate] Goodbye.

1530
01:38:57,723 --> 01:38:59,558
See you at graduation, Auggie.

1531
01:39:03,646 --> 01:39:05,981
Looking sharp.

1532
01:39:06,065 --> 01:39:07,149
Thanks, Dad.

1533
01:39:07,232 --> 01:39:08,651
I'm talking about me.

1534
01:39:08,734 --> 01:39:11,945
Hey! Ah, you look good, too.

1535
01:39:12,029 --> 01:39:16,700
I think it's safe to say
the Pullman men are crushing it today.

1536
01:39:20,079 --> 01:39:22,748
-You've come a long way, huh?
-Yeah.

1537
01:39:25,834 --> 01:39:29,421
Auggie, I am proud of you
for sticking it out.

1538
01:39:29,505 --> 01:39:30,964
You didn't think I would, did you?

1539
01:39:31,048 --> 01:39:32,424
'Course I did.

1540
01:39:35,427 --> 01:39:36,387
Okay, well, come on.

1541
01:39:36,470 --> 01:39:38,847
You gotta admit
when you started you were still wearing

1542
01:39:38,931 --> 01:39:40,849
the astronaut helmet in public.

1543
01:39:41,517 --> 01:39:44,728
I love that helmet.
I wish I knew where it was.

1544
01:39:48,732 --> 01:39:49,817
It's in my office.

1545
01:39:49,900 --> 01:39:53,654
What? Dad! That was a gift.
You had no right to hide it!

1546
01:39:53,737 --> 01:39:55,531
Auggie, Auggie, please, don't be mad.

1547
01:39:55,614 --> 01:39:58,951
You gotta understand,
you were wearing it all the time.

1548
01:39:59,034 --> 01:40:00,744
I never got to see you any more.

1549
01:40:00,828 --> 01:40:02,996
I missed your face.

1550
01:40:03,080 --> 01:40:05,791
I know you don't always like it,
but I love it.

1551
01:40:05,874 --> 01:40:07,918
It's my son's face.

1552
01:40:10,921 --> 01:40:12,631
I wanna see it.

1553
01:40:15,634 --> 01:40:16,802
Do you forgive me?

1554
01:40:16,885 --> 01:40:18,053
No.

1555
01:40:21,098 --> 01:40:22,057
Yes.

1556
01:40:24,101 --> 01:40:25,394
Does Mom know?

1557
01:40:25,477 --> 01:40:27,062
[whispers] No. God, no, she'd kill me.

1558
01:40:28,480 --> 01:40:31,608
But I can maybe find it,
if you need it back.

1559
01:40:31,692 --> 01:40:32,735
That's okay.

1560
01:40:43,996 --> 01:40:46,165
[choir singing]
Follow the day 

1561
01:40:47,374 --> 01:40:51,336
Follow the day and reach for the sun!

1562
01:40:51,420 --> 01:40:54,548
You don't see me flyin' to the red

1563
01:40:54,631 --> 01:40:57,593
One more you're done

1564
01:40:57,676 --> 01:40:59,678
Just follow the day and...

1565
01:40:59,762 --> 01:41:01,764
-[whispers] Mom.
-[whispers] Yes?

1566
01:41:01,847 --> 01:41:03,056
Thank you.

1567
01:41:04,808 --> 01:41:05,893
For what?

1568
01:41:05,976 --> 01:41:07,603
Making me go to school.

1569
01:41:11,064 --> 01:41:13,025
I was so mad at you sometimes.

1570
01:41:13,108 --> 01:41:15,110
But I'm really happy to be here.

1571
01:41:17,654 --> 01:41:19,281
You really are a wonder, Auggie.

1572
01:41:21,033 --> 01:41:22,284
You are a wonder.

1573
01:41:23,702 --> 01:41:25,370
Follow the day

1574
01:41:27,706 --> 01:41:32,085
Follow the day and reach for the sun!

1575
01:41:43,597 --> 01:41:45,265
Whoo! [chuckles]

1576
01:41:45,641 --> 01:41:46,934
Thank you, choir.

1577
01:41:47,976 --> 01:41:49,269
That was beautiful.

1578
01:41:50,938 --> 01:41:55,984
Ladies, gentlemen,
boys and girls, graduates.

1579
01:41:58,445 --> 01:42:02,157
Final award this morning
is the Henry Ward Beecher medal

1580
01:42:03,200 --> 01:42:08,080
to honour students
who have been notable or exemplary.

1581
01:42:09,122 --> 01:42:13,836
Usually, it's a "good works,"
a service award.

1582
01:42:15,254 --> 01:42:18,215
But I came upon a passage that he wrote,

1583
01:42:18,298 --> 01:42:21,510
which made me realize that good works

1584
01:42:23,178 --> 01:42:24,388
come in many forms.

1585
01:42:26,765 --> 01:42:28,600
"Greatness," he wrote,

1586
01:42:29,726 --> 01:42:31,979
"lies not in being strong

1587
01:42:33,355 --> 01:42:36,984
but in the right using of strength.

1588
01:42:37,985 --> 01:42:41,280
He or she is the greatest

1589
01:42:42,531 --> 01:42:45,534
whose strength carries up the most hearts

1590
01:42:46,952 --> 01:42:50,080
by the attraction of his own."

1591
01:42:54,126 --> 01:43:00,215
Without further ado, this year,
I am very proud

1592
01:43:00,299 --> 01:43:04,845
to award the Henry Ward Beecher medal

1593
01:43:04,928 --> 01:43:08,390
to the student whose quiet strength

1594
01:43:09,641 --> 01:43:11,977
has carried up the most hearts.

1595
01:43:12,936 --> 01:43:14,730
So,

1596
01:43:14,813 --> 01:43:18,567
will August Pullman please come
up here to receive this award?

1597
01:43:18,650 --> 01:43:20,736
[all cheering and applauding]

1598
01:43:24,948 --> 01:43:26,325
Whoo!

1599
01:43:52,809 --> 01:43:54,311
You're the best, dude!

1600
01:43:59,191 --> 01:44:03,737
[Auggie] Walking up towards 
that stage, I felt like I was floating.

1601
01:44:03,820 --> 01:44:06,323
My heart was beating so fast.

1602
01:44:06,406 --> 01:44:09,660
I didn't really understand
why I was getting a medal.

1603
01:44:09,743 --> 01:44:12,037
It's not like I blew up the Death Star.

1604
01:44:13,121 --> 01:44:17,250
All I did was get through fifth grade, 
just like everyone else here.

1605
01:44:17,334 --> 01:44:18,377
Congratulations.

1606
01:44:20,504 --> 01:44:22,839
Here you go. That's for you.

1607
01:44:22,923 --> 01:44:25,342
[Auggie] Then again, 
maybe that's kind of the point.

1608
01:44:27,219 --> 01:44:30,722
Maybe the truth is,
I'm really not so ordinary.

1609
01:44:32,140 --> 01:44:34,851
Maybe if we knew 
what other people were thinking

1610
01:44:34,935 --> 01:44:37,312
we'd know that no one's ordinary.

1611
01:44:37,396 --> 01:44:41,692
And we all deserve a standing ovation
at least once in our lives.

1612
01:44:43,485 --> 01:44:45,028
My friends do.

1613
01:44:49,491 --> 01:44:51,243
My teachers do.

1614
01:44:52,327 --> 01:44:54,746
My sister does
for always being there for me.

1615
01:44:56,123 --> 01:44:59,167
My dad does for always making us laugh.

1616
01:45:00,460 --> 01:45:02,170
And my mom does the most.

1617
01:45:02,254 --> 01:45:05,090
For never giving up. On anything.

1618
01:45:05,173 --> 01:45:06,341
Especially me.

1619
01:45:08,176 --> 01:45:11,972
It's like that last precept
Mr Browne gave us.

1620
01:45:12,097 --> 01:45:15,642
Be kind, 
for everyone is fighting a hard battle.

1621
01:45:16,601 --> 01:45:19,104
And if you really wanna see
what people are,

1622
01:45:20,313 --> 01:45:24,276
all you have to do... is look.

